<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-476-152  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 476 152.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  July 31 1989 n230 p38(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>T-3: bigger and better bandwidth. (includes related article on theT-3 pricing war)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Messmer, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies with burgeoning information needs are beginning to turnto fiber-optic T-3 networks, or are leasing T-3 circuits fromnetwork providers, in hopes of saving money while satisfying theircompanies' growing bandwidth requirements.andP;  T-3, or Digital Signal3 (DS3), provides a high-capacity transmission pipeline which cancarry 44.736M-bits of data per second.andP;  A single T-3 circuit costsabout the same as seven T-1 circuits, allowing a company topurchase four times as much bandwidth for the dollar.andP;  Mostcompanies do not yet require that much bandwidth, however, andmonthly T-3 rates can reach $6,000.andP;  T-3 modes of transportinclude fiber optics, microwave, satellite, coaxial cable andinfrared technology.andP;  Among its uses are: image-orientedapplications, videoconferencing, linking local and wide areanetworks, and computer-aided design and computer-aidedengineering.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsBandwidthDigital CommunicationsCost Benefit AnalysisNew TechniqueApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Sample pricing for T-3 circuits. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>